<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Aden Radio Claims Sudan Sent Supplies to North </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Aden Radio Claims Sudan Sent Supplies to North </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   EA0306204194 Aden Democratic Republic of Yemen Radio Network 
in Arabic 1700 GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> EA0306204194 </F>
<F P=104>  Aden Democratic Republic of Yemen Radio Network 
in Arabic 1700 GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=105> Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Well-informed political and military sources have 
spoken about the political and military dilemma in which the 
ruling regime in Sanaa has found itself because it insists on 
continuing the war against the Democratic Republic of Yemen by 
seeking more military supplies. These sources linked the recent 
visits of Yahya Husayn al-Arashi, member of the Permanent 
Committee of the General People's Congress, and Muhammad 
'Abdallah (al-Yadumi), the third man in the Yemeni Alliance for 
Reform [al-Tajammu al-Yamani Li-al-Islah] to Khartoum and the 
visit paid to Sanaa today by the Sudanese minister of 
information, 'Abd-al-Basit Sabdarat, as the envoy of Sudanese 
President Lieutenant General 'Umar Hasan al-Bashir. The sources 
said the visit was linked to the question of military supplies 
sent from Sudan to the Sanaa regime. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

