<F P=100> IRAQ </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kurdish Leaders Barzani, Talabani Meet in Irbil </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kurdish Leaders Barzani, Talabani Meet in Irbil </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0506200294 Paris AFP in English 1924 GMT 5 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0506200294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Irbil, Iraq, June 5 (AFP) -- Iraqi Kurdistan's main 
leaders, Mas'ud Barzani and Jalal Talabani, met here Sunday for 
the first time since fierce clashes broke out between their 
rival factions a month ago. 
  The meeting in the northern Iraqi town of Irbil took place 
at 
the initiative of the Iraqi National Congress (INC), a coalition 
of Arab and Kurdish groups opposed to President Saddam Husayn. 
  The INC announced after the talks that a new joint operation 
room was being formed to implement a ceasefire between Barzani's 
Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP) and Talabani's Patriotic Union 
of Kurdistan (PUK). 
  The PUK leader, abroad when the fighting broke out in early 
May, was airlifted back to northern Iraq last week on board a 
Turkish helicopter to overfly KDP-controlled areas. 
  After several ceasefire accords, calm returned to most of 
Iraqi Kurdistan at the end of May. But fresh clashes erupted 
Saturday in the regions of Halabjah and Qal'at al-Dizah, near 
the Iranian border, according to the CNI. 
  The CNI says more than 600 people are believed to been 
killed 
in the power struggle between the PUK and KDP, which have 
controlled northern Iraq in defiance of Baghdad since the 
aftermath of the 1991 Gulf War. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

