<F P=100> SYRIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Comments on Status of Peace Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Comments on Status of Peace Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM0306112894 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 3 Jun 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> PM0306112894 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Sawsan Abu-Husayn report: "Al-Shar' Tells AL-SHARQ </F>
AL-AWSAT: We Will Not Resume Negotiations Before Full 
Withdrawal Is Agreed To"] 
  [Text] Cairo -- Syrian Foreign Minister Faruq al-Shar' has 
said that his country will not resume its negotiations with 
Israel before receiving its final reply vis-a-vis the full 
withdrawal to the 4 June 1967 lines. In an exclusive statement 
to AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT he said: "Then we would be able to discuss 
any Israeli proposal." 
  On his country's acceptance of a phased Israeli withdrawal 
within a reasonable period, the Syrian foreign minister said 
that his country "is not at present looking for a phased 
withdrawal or its duration. We are awaiting U.S. Secretary of 
State Warren Christopher's visit to the region, especially as he 
has promised to achieve positive results during his upcoming 
tour." 
  Al-Shar' said: "Israel still has not announced its 
willingness to withdraw fully from the Golan, while we accept a 
phased Israeli withdrawal, but the question is: Is it all the 
Golan or are there other areas which Israel believes subject to 
the security clauses?" 
  On Arab coordination al-Shar' said: "We are committed to it. 
We made contacts with Jordan before the Jordanian monarch, King 
Husayn, visited Damascus. And Lebanese President Ilyas 
al-Hirawi and his prime minister held a meeting with President 
Hafiz al-Asad. We also coordinate with Egypt from time to time 
by telephone or through frequent meetings. All this falls 
within the framework of assessing the situation and the extent 
of Israel's seriousness in entering into a comprehensive, full, 
and nondeficient peace with the Arab states." 
  Al-Shar' denied any plan to meet with Faruq Qaddumi in Syria 
within days in the framework of Palestinian-Syrian coordination. 
  On Syria's mediation role between Egypt and Iran he said: 
"Neither party has entrusted us with that matter. As for our 
relations with Iran, they are extremely good and proceeding on 
parallel lines vis-a-vis the important issues in the region." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

