<F P=100> India </F>
<H3> <TI>   JKLF President Escapes Assassination in Kashmir </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    JKLF President Escapes Assassination in Kashmir </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK0406083994 Delhi All India Radio Network in English 1530 
GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0406083994 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In Kashmir, a second attempt was made on the life 
of the banned JKLF [Jammu and Kashmir Liberation Front] 
president, Mr. Yasin Malik, in Srinagar today when he was 
leading a processing to the Idgah graveyard. One of his 
associates died and several were injured when extremists 
showered bullets on them at Kankahi Mohallah. After the 
incident, Mr. Malik was whisked away to a safe place by his 
supporters. Later, he told a press conference that his 
attackers belong to the pro-Pakistan extremist outfit, the 
Hezbul Mojahedin. Yesterday, Mr. Malik had a narrow escape when 
the Hezbul Mojahedin tried to kidnap him from a hospital, but 
his supporters foiled the attempt. 
  [Hong Kong AFP in English 1618 GMT 3 Jun 94, in a 
Srinagar-datelined report, adds the following: "A pro-Pakistani 
Moslem rebel group Friday denied trying to kill a rival 
separatist leader after dragging him out of hospital and later 
firing on a march organised by him in this Kashmir summer 
capital. 
  "The Hizbul Mujahideen group said the Thursday attempt on 
the 
life of Yasin Malik, the leader of the powerful Jammu and 
Kashmir Liberation Front (JKLF), and the attack on a rally a day 
later, were staged by disgruntled JKLF members. 
  "`Lobbyism in the JKLF was responsible for the attacks,' a 
trenchant Hizbul Mujahideen statement said. `JKLF workers tried 
to kill Yasin Malik on Thursday and Friday.' 
  "Hizb spokesman Mohammed Sadiq said Malik's charges were 
baseless and an attempt to gain public sympathy and coverage in 
the media. 
  "`It is a ploy,' he said, referring to Malik's allegations 
that Hizbul Mujahideen activists had again targeted him Friday 
during an attack on a procession which killed at least two 
militants and injured four. 
  "`If it is proved that Hizbul men were involved, we will try 
them,' Sadiq added. 
  "Malik, who advocates an independent Kashmir unlike most 
other groups who want the state to accede to Pakistan, announced 
a three-day strike from Saturday to protest the attack by `black 
sheep and criminals.' 
  "He also announced a fast until the 70-odd warring militant 
outfits reorganised themselves under three heads: those 
favouring independence for Kashmir, those wanting to join 
Pakistan, and a third `general category.'"] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

