<H3> <TI>   Northern Troops Move Closer to Aden </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Northern Troops Move Closer to Aden </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0306132394 Paris AFP in English 1145 GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0306132394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Aden, June 3 (AFP) -- Northern Yemeni forces 
fought their way closer to the south's bastion of Aden on Friday 
[3 June] after trading rocket and artillery fire with southern 
troops, despite both sides' acceptance of a UN ceasefire call. 
  Northern army units loyal to President 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih 
moved to within 15 kilometers (nine miles) of Aden, as a 
northern minister said they were now in a position to capture 
the city after four weeks of civil war. 
  Salih's troops captured the villages of al-Waht, 20 
kilometers (12 miles) northwest of Aden, and Lahij, 30 
kilometers (19 miles) north of the city, southern commanders 
confirmed. 
  Dozens of people were killed in the battle for the two 
villages on Thursday and Friday, and hundreds of villagers fled 
the fighting. 
  Southern troops loyal to the president's rival 'Ali Salim 
al-Bid said they were forced back to Bi'r Nasir, some 15 
kilometers (nine miles) north of Aden. 
  Northern troops advancing on Aden from the east also moved 
forward to within 30 kilometers (19 miles) of the port city 
after fighting in the Abyan region. 
  Two surface-to-surface missiles were fired at Aden in a dawn 
attack Friday, without causing casualties. 
  A military spokesman in Aden, capital of a breakaway 
southern 
state, said southern anti-aircraft fire intercepted one missile 
while the other landed in an uninhabited area of desert. 
  In Sanaa, Information Minister Hasan al-Lawzi told reporters 
that northern forces were now "able to enter the city, but they 
are awaiting a political decision." 
  Salih's troops have mounted "fierce offensives on all 
fronts, 
destroying villages and killing civilians," the southern command 
charged in a statement. "We are resisting with all our strength 
to protect our land and our honour." 
  A military spokesman in Aden said southern forces on 
Thursday 
repelled an offensive by northern troops in the oil region of 
Shabwah, 300 kilometers (180 miles) northeast of Aden. 
  The spokesman told Aden Radio that the northern troops 
commander in Shabwah, Colonel Muhammad Salim al-'Arif, lost his 
right arm in the fighting, while "several" northern soldiers 
were killed or injured. 
  Southern army units destroyed four tanks and three troop 
carriers and captured two tanks and several northern army 
vehicles, the spokesman added. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

