<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Council Reviews UNSC Resolution </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Council Reviews UNSC Resolution </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN0206182594 Sanaa Yemeni Republic Radio Network in Arabic 
1700 GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN0206182594 </F>
<F P=104>  Sanaa Yemeni Republic Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Council of Ministers resumed its extraordinary 
meeting this afternoon under Acting Prime Minister Dr. Muhammad 
Sa'id al-'Attar to examine UN Security Council [UNSC] Resolution 
924 adopted in its session No. 3,386 held on 1 June. 
  After an exchange of views, the Council expressed its 
appreciation for the resolution, which was based on the 
provisions enshrined in the UN Charter, particularly the 
Republic of Yemen's sovereignty, independence, and territorial 
integrity. 
  The following is the text of the resolution: 
  In the name of God, the merciful, the compassionate. 
  Text of UNSC Resolution No. 924 of 1994, unanimously adopted 
by the UNSC at its session No. 3,386 held on 1 June 1994. 
  Having examined the situation in the Republic of Yemen; 
Taking into account the purposes and principles of the UN 
Charter; Extremely concerned over the tragic death of innocent 
civilians; Appreciative of the efforts under way by the Arab 
League, the Gulf Cooperation Council, the Islamic Conference 
Organization, neighboring countries, and other concerned 
countries to contribute to a solution to the conflict through 
peaceful means and ensure the achievement of peace and stability 
in the Republic of Yemen; Realizing that continuation of the 
situation there can jeopardize peace and security in the region, 
the UNSC: 
  1. Calls for an immediate cease-fire. 
  2. Urges an immediate halt to the supply of arms and other 
equipment that could contribute to the prolongation of the 
conflict. 
  3. Reminds all those concerned that political disputes 
cannot be resolved by force, and urges them to immediately 
return to the negotiating table so that they may resolve their 
disputes by peaceful means and reestablish peace and stability. 
  4. Calls upon the UN secretary general to dispatch a 
fact-finding mission to the region at the earliest possible 
opportunity to assess the prospects for renewed dialogue among 
all concerned parties so that they may make additional efforts 
to resolve their disputes. 
  5. Urges the UN secretary general to submit a report on the 
situation at the appropriate time, but within a period not 
exceeding one week as of the completion of the fact-finding 
mission. 
  6. Decides to keep the issue under practical consideration. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-36012 </DOCNO>
