<F P=100> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   *Goods Exported From Bandar 'Abbas Up 45 Percent </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    *Goods Exported From Bandar 'Abbas Up 45 Percent </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   94LA0166F Tehran KEYHAN-E HAVA'I in Persian 20 Apr 94 p 10 </F>
<F P=103> 94LA0166F </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran KEYHAN-E HAVA'I </F>
<F P=105>  Persian </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

  [Text] Bandar 'Abbas, 22 Farvardin [11 April] -- IRNA: The 
province of Hormozegan exported 1.368 million tons of goods 
through customs offices in the year 1372 [21 March 1993-20 March 
1994], and this figure represents 45-percent growth compared to 
the same period last year. 
  Mohammad Hoseyn Bagh-Enayat, supervisor of the customs 
offices of the province of Hormozegan, Yazd and Kerman, 
announced the above. He said: These goods include handicrafts, 
pistachios, various kinds of fruit, summer vegetables, dates, 
machine-made carpets, clothing, leather shoes and garments, 
plant seeds, and mineral substances, which were exported to the 
European nations, Scandinavia, and the Persian Gulf Emirates. 
  He added: The value of export goods is estimated at 
40,266,354 rials [R], and this figure represents 52.2-percent 
growth compared to the year 1371 [21 March 1992-20 March 1993]. 
  Bagh-Enayat added: In the year 1372 more than 6.896 million 
tons of imported goods valued at 358 billion tumans was released 
through customs in the province of Hormozegan, representing a 
decrease of 48 percent by weight compared to the same period in 
the year 1371. 
  He added: The imported goods include sugar, rice, edible 
oil, 
chemical fertilizer, herbicides, raw materials for industrial 
and producing units, and various types of vehicles. 
  He added: Last year 28,145 various vehicles, cranes, 
tankers, 
forklifts, and heavy road-building equipment were cleared 
through Bandar 'Abbas customs. 
  Bagh-Enayat announced that the revenues at the units 
affiliated with customs in the year 1372 through the provinces 
of Yazd, Kerman, and Hormozegan totaled R298.128 billion. 
  He added: Last year 98,155 tons of goods went through Bandar 
'Abbas customs to Afghanistan and the Central Asian nations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

