<F P=100> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   *Over 1,000 Iranians Return From Germany </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    *Over 1,000 Iranians Return From Germany </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   94LA0168C Tehran KEYHAN-E HAVA'I in Persian 11 May 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> 94LA0168C </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran KEYHAN-E HAVA'I </F>
<F P=105>  Persian </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

  [Text] 17 Ordibehesht [7 May] KEYHAN-E HAVA'I News Service 
-- Last year more than 2,000 compatriots living in Germany 
obtained Iranian visas from Iran's representatives in this 
country after continued asylum was denied to them. Half of them 
have returned to the country. 
  The public relations office of Iran's Embassy in Bonn 
reports 
that these people left Iran without authorization for various 
reasons, including such things as the fact that they were 
forbidden to leave, their obligatory military service status was 
unclear or they were planning to continue their educations. 
However, following KEYHAN-E HAVA'I's interview with Deputy 
Foreign Minister Manuchehr Motaki and the clear announcement of 
the Iranian Government's new policy to grant Iranian visas to 
all compatriots outside the country lacking identity papers, 
they went to our country's representative offices in Germany and 
obtained visas. 
  According to the report from the public relations office of 
the Iranian Embassy in Bonn, last year more than 1,000 Iranians 
who obtained visas returned to the country from Germany. 
  Based on the same report, thousands of Iranians living in 
Germany, using the facilities created for them, are happily 
reporting to Iran's Embassy and Consulates and preparing to go 
to Iran with hopes of returning to the embrace of their families. 
  Also, one month prior to this, KEYHAN-E HAVA'I reported the 
issuance of visas for 150 compatriots living in Rome and the 
return of many of them to Iran. 
  It is worth mentioning that on page 1 of KEYHAN-E HAVA'I 
issue 1,078 it was reported that the number of Iranians living 
in Germany who obtained Iranian visas last year was 1,000, but 
the correct figure is 2,000. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

