<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   South Minister on `Suspicions' of CW Use by North </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    South Minister on `Suspicions' of CW Use by North </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM0306140094 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 3 Jun 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> PM0306140094 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Reports by 'Abdallah Hammudah, Lutfi Shatarah, Hanan </F>
al-Badri, and Salih Qallab: "Massacre in Aden, Emigration From 
Sanaa, and Accusations of Use of Chemical Weapons"] 
  [Excerpts] London, New York, Amman, Aden, Sanaa, AL-SHARQ 
AL-AWSAT -- Fierce fighting continued yesterday in numerous 
areas in Lahij Government, north of Aden. Meanwhile the Yemeni 
Government in Sanaa announced its acceptance of Security Council 
Resolution 924 calling for a cease-fire between northern and 
southern forces. [passage omitted] 
  Well-informed sources have told AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT that the 
fierce fighting in Tawr al-Bahah, Lahij Governorate, is 
attributable to the attempt by four northern battalions to 
advance toward Aden through al-Hawtah, led by Colonel 'Ali 
Muhsin al-Ahmar, commander of the 1st Tank Division and 
half-brother of the Yemeni president. So southern forces worked 
to encircle these units in a bid to capture 'Ali Muhsin 
al-Ahmar, especially as reports had said that a number of 
northern commanders who are the Yemeni president's uncles were 
with him. 
  These developments coincided with accusations exchanged 
between the northern and southern leaderships about the use of 
banned weapons. The accusations included a statement by Judge 
Hammud al-Hattar in Sanaa that southern forces are using napalm 
bombs in their attacks on northern units. He said that there 
"is irrefutable evidence of that." Meanwhile Southern Defense 
Minister Brigadier Haytham Qasim Tahir expressed his suspicions 
that northern forces are using chemical weapons. He added that 
"these suspicions are justifiable." 
  Brig. Haytham said that "our suspicions are reinforced by 
the 
distinct and special relationship between 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih 
and Iraqi President Saddam Husayn, who used these weapons 
against the Kurds in 1988." [passage omitted] 
  High-ranking southern leaders have denied reports which have 
aroused alarm among some circles about an advance by northern 
forces toward the Dar Sa'd area. They told AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT 
over the telephone: "How can that happen, when Democratic Yemen 
formed its new government yesterday -- a proof that matters are 
stable," despite the ongoing fighting there. 
  Southern officials said that some northern militias 
belonging 
to the Yemeni Reform Grouping have stormed Sabr prison in the 
Tawr al-Bahah area and freed some prisoners. They added that 
Aden forces clashed with them. They confirmed that conditions 
are now calm there. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-36044 </DOCNO>
