<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   North Releases Casualty Figures for Conflict </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    North Releases Casualty Figures for Conflict </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0506121694 Paris AFP in English 1133 GMT 5 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0506121694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sanaa, June 5 (AFP) -- Six-hundred-and-thirteen 
soldiers loyal to northern President 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih have 
been killed and 2,030 wounded in Yemen's month-old civil war, 
officials said in the first official toll published here Sunday 
[5 June]. 
  Another 1,200 northern troops have been reported missing 
while 901 are being held prisoner by southern forces backing 
Salih's rival 'Ali Salim al-Bid, a military spokesman told the 
northern-controlled SABA' news agency. 
  He said the number of prisoners being held in "concentration 
camps in Aden" had been supplied by the International Committee 
of the Red Cross. 
  It was the first official, if partial, toll to be given 
since 
fighting broke out on May 5. 
  Late Saturday a southern leader said in Cairo that 80,000 
people had been killed, wounded or made homeless in the 
fighting, without giving a breakdown. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

