<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   NAM Conference Issues Communique, Concludes </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    NAM Conference Issues Communique, Concludes </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Proposal for Bosnia Conference Adopted </H4>

<F P=102> BK0306135094 Kuala Lumpur BERNAMA in English 0707 GMT 3 Jun 
94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0306135094 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur BERNAMA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Kuala Lumpur, June 3 (OANA-BERNAMA) -- The 
Non-Aligned Movement (NAM) meeting in Cairo has unanimously 
adopted Malaysia's proposal that an international conference be 
held on Bosnia-Herzegovina, Foreign Minister Abdullah Ahmad 
Badawi said Friday [3 June]. 
  This is the first time that a large organisation like NAM 
has 
formally adopted our proposal to promote and initiate the 
hosting of the international conference, he said in a telephone 
interview from here. 
  With the agreement, it means that NAM, which has 108 
members, 
is prepared to make efforts to hold the conference which has all 
along been only proposed by several other parties. 
  Abdullah is happy with the support given to Malaysia by 
heads 
of delegation when the proposal was discussed on Wednesday. 
  He said that the contact group of the Islamic Conference 
Organisation (IOC) had also expressed support for Malaysia's 
proposal that NAM initiate the hosting of the international 
conference. 
  The agreement was reached at the group's informal meeting 
where the Bosnian delegates gave a briefing on the latest 
situation in their country. 
  The group had also discussed matters to be included in the 
NAM's final document on Bosnia-Herzegovina, he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

