<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   NAM Conference Issues Communique, Concludes </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    NAM Conference Issues Communique, Concludes </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Israeli Raids on Lebanon Condemned </H4>

<F P=102> NC0306121494 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1025 GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0306121494 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 3 Jun (MENA) -- The Nonaligned Movement's 
foreign ministers conference has condemned the Israeli air raids 
on south Lebanon. In a resolution passed today, the conference 
stresses its complete solidarity with the Lebanese Government 
and people, and support for Lebanon in defending its sovereignty 
by all available means. 
  The conference calls on the UN Security Council and the 
cosponsors of the peace conference in the Middle East, "the 
United States and Russia" to move immediately to put an end to 
Israeli aggression, which is against the UN Charter and is 
designed to torpedo the peace process. The resolution calls for 
saving the peace process from collapse. 
  The resolution expresses the nonaligned conference's concern 
over the Israeli acts of aggression against Lebanese towns and 
villages. It said that the new massacre committed by Israel and 
previous kidnappings and acts of terror are no doubt intended to 
torpedo the peace process. 
  Hisham Dimashqiyah, Lebanese ambassador in Cairo and head of 
the Lebanese delegation to the nonaligned conference, delivered 
a speech at the conference. He said that by its repeated acts 
of aggression against south Lebanon Israel is violating 
Lebanon's sovereignty and defying the peace process. He called 
on the conference to pass a resolution strongly condemning 
Israeli aggression and stressing solidarity with the Lebanese 
people in defending their sovereignty by all available means. 
  The foreign ministers and heads of delegations of Syria, 
Jordan, Saudi Arabia, Egypt, Palestine, Morocco, and Yemen 
delivered speeches in which they expressed support for Lebanon 
and called on the conference to pass an unequivocal resolution 
condemning Israeli aggression against south Lebanon. They also 
stressed that they support the Lebanese authorities efforts to 
extend their control throughout Lebanon. 
  Dimashqiyah told MENA that the Israeli aggression against 
Lebanon will impact negatively on the peace process in the 
Middle East, particularly the Lebanese track. 
  Responding to a question on Lebanon's intention to freeze 
the 
peace talks' Lebanese-Israeli track, Dimashqiyah said that 
freezing the negotiations may happen afer consultations among 
the higher Lebanese authorities, the Government, and the Chamber 
of Deputies. He said that the current Israeli air raids on 
Lebanon are part of a series of recurring acts of aggression, 
along with kidnappings of citizens and other air raids that kill 
and wound dozens of Lebanese. He said that the Lebanese Army is 
in a state of alert to repulse any aggression in cooperation 
with the Syrian forces operating in Lebanon. He noted that 
Israel uses any provocations or clashes on the border as a 
pretext to launch acts of aggression deep inside Lebanese 
territory, not just provocations in areas at the borders. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-36092 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes109yy_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-109 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  3 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   NAM Conference Issues Communique, Concludes </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    NAM Conference Issues Communique, Concludes </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Syrian, Others View Israeli Assaults </H4>

<F P=102> NC0306133794 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1147 GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0306133794 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 3 Jun (MENA) -- The Nonaligned Movement's 
foreign ministers 11th conference devoted much of its final 
session to the issue of the Israeli raids against south Lebanon. 
Several foreign ministers and delegation heads addressed the 
session on this subject. 
  Head of the Lebanese delegation Hisham Dimashqiyah remarked 
that yesterday's Israeli aggression against the country 
constitutes a declaration of war. He warned that the peace 
process is endangered and that the UN Security Council and the 
United States and Russia, the two sponsors of the peace 
conference, must put pressure on Israel. 
  Syrian Foreign Minister Faruq al-Shar' said that the Israeli 
aggression against Lebanon is not directed against one 
particular country but against the entire world community and 
the cosponsors of the peace conference. He added that this is 
not the first such aggression and will not be the last and that 
Israel's repeated assaults on the Arab parties participating in 
the peace process illustrate the Israeli design to ruin the 
peace process and smother the opportunity to attain peace. 
  Head of the Egyptian delegation Nabil al-'Arabi emphasized 
his country's backing for Lebanon and its support for a 
comprehensive and just Middle East peace. He said Israel must 
halt these acts, which threaten the peace operation and 
contravene international law. He pointed out that peacemaking 
needs a favorable climate and the attack on Lebanon posed a 
threat to the Lebanese nation. 
  The head of the Saudi delegation said he adds his voice to 
that of the other delegation heads in expressing profound 
concern and strong condemnation of the Israeli aggression 
against Lebanon. He stressed that Saudi Arabia supports the 
Lebanese people and wants the peace process to continue. He 
urged that UN Security Council Resolution 425, which provides 
for Israeli withdrawal from south Lebanon, be implemented. 
  PLO Political Department head Faruq Qaddumi accused Israel 
of 
deceiving the world. He said what is really happening between 
Israel and Palestine now is a new form of battle which, although 
it involves no violence, is a fresh stage of struggle. 
  Qaddumi added that Israel's acts of piracy in Lebanon, such 
as its abduction of Lebanese citizens, prove that it does not 
seek peace but is persisting in its efforts to derail the peace 
process. He said regional peace is still far away. 
  The head of the Libyan delegation reiterated support for 
Lebanon, condemned Israel, and urged the Security Council, the 
United States, and Russia to intervene to salvage the peace 
operation. 
  The Yemeni and Moroccan foreign ministers also declared 
support for Lebanon. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

