<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Musa on Yemen Situation, African Debts Repayment </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Musa on Yemen Situation, African Debts Repayment </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0706103094 Cairo MENA in Arabic 0953 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0706103094 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Tunis, 7 Jun (MENA)--Foreign Minister 'Amr Musa 
has stated that Egypt stands by Yemen's unity, noting that this 
unity cannot be preserved by shedding more blood. He said Egypt 
supports international and Arab legitimacy in this and other 
issues. 
  In an interview with the Tunisian newspaper AL-RA'Y AL-'AMM 
today, Musa said fear of Arabizing or internationalizing the 
Yemeni crisis should not be a justification for the Arabs to sit 
with their hands tied without working to stem the bloodshed in 
fraternal Yemen. 
  He added that the fear of Arabizing the crisis is not a 
justification for an indifferent stand which some are asking us 
to adopt and leave the brothers fight each other. He went on: 
We had feared Arabizing and internationalizing the crisis in 
the Gulf and are now doing the same thing as if we are invited 
to let Arab blood spill all the time. [passage omitted] 
  On the $275-billion African debts, Musa emphasized the need 
to repay them according to schedules leading to the revival of 
African economies. He urged the industrial nations to set an 
annual percentage to help development processes in African 
states reach the international target figure of 0.7 per cent of 
the gross national product. He noted that this percentage 
barely reaches 0.3 despite these countries' pledges in various 
international forums. 
  The foreign minister said Egypt has put forth several 
proposals to the OAU, including one on the need to adopt 
specific measures urging the international community to help 
resolve the African debt problem. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

