<F P=100> SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Afghanistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   AL-THAWRAH: Yemeni War `Could Have Been Averted' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    AL-THAWRAH: Yemeni War `Could Have Been Averted' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN0406080894 Damascus Syrian Arab Republic Radio Network in 
Arabic 0450 GMT 4 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN0406080894 </F>
<F P=104>  Damascus Syrian Arab Republic Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the press review] </F>
  [Text] In a commentary today, the newspaper AL-THAWRAH 
writes on the fighting raging in Yemen. It stresses that this 
war, which is not in the interest of Yemen or its people, could 
have been averted. 
  After explaining the effects of this war on Yemen's economy, 
AL- THAWRAH calls on the Yemeni leadership to rise to the level 
of its national and pan-Arab responsibility, and to respond to 
the homeland's call and the UN Security Council's demand to stop 
the massacres and destruction. 
  The Yemeni people, who are concerned about unity, are 
certain 
that what is taking place is not for the sake of unity, which 
they chose and sought for their future so that they might enjoy 
safety, security, and progress in all walks of life. 
  AL-THAWRAH stresses that the continuation of this war 
threatens the fabric of the Yemeni homeland by fomenting 
sedition and hostility among the sons of the one homeland. 
  Concluding, AL-THAWRAH says: The Yemeni leadership must take 
into consideration the results of continued fighting in terms of 
casting doubts on the possibility of achieving Arab unity, and 
consequently, damaging the credibility of the principle of Arab 
unity, and harming the Arabs' image in the world. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

