<H3> <TI>   Gaza Police Chief Curbs Mosques Political Activity </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Gaza Police Chief Curbs Mosques Political Activity </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA0606191894 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 1100 GMT 6 Jun 
94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0606191894 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] General Nasr Yusuf, commander of the Palestinian 
police force, has ordered all the imams in Gaza Strip mosques to 
halt all political activity in the mosques and to stop issuing 
calls against the autonomy authorities over loudspeakers. Our 
correspondent Nisim Qeynan reports that Nasr Yusuf also ordered 
to shut down the mosques after the last daily prayer, which 
usually ends at 2100. He also warned the imams against 
nonreligious activity in the mosques. The Islamic movement in 
the Gaza Strip has expressed opposition to and anger over 
Yusuf's directives and over the fact that the Palestinian police 
is hampering its activity. 
  [Tel Aviv IDF Radio in Hebrew at 1130 GMT on 6 June adds: 
"Nasr Yusuf, commander of the Palestinian police in Gaza, has 
been removed from his position as the Palestinian national 
security commander [as heard], apparently against the background 
of the sharp verbal clashes between him and Hamas (Islamic 
Resistance Movement). He will be replaced by 'Abd-al-Razzaq 
al-Majayirah, who headed the Palestinian delegation for security 
talks with Israel. Recently there have been sharp clashes 
between Nasr Yusuf and extremist Muslims in Gaza against the 
background of Yusuf's demand to disarm Hamas and Islamic Jihad 
activists, and also in the wake of the incarceration of Hani 
al-'Abd, an Islamic Jihad activist. This is reported by our 
Arab Affairs correspondent Oren Kohen."] 

</TEXT>

