<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   North Accuses South of Violating Cease-Fire </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    North Accuses South of Violating Cease-Fire </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN0706083694 Amman Radio Jordan in English 0800 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> JN0706083694 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman Radio Jordan </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A top Yemeni official has said that southern 
warplanes bombarded government forces this morning, violating an 
hours' old unilateral cease-fire aimed at ending Yemen's civil 
war. 
  Planning Minister 'Abd-al-Karim al-Iryani told the press 
that 
Aden aircraft were bombarding all around since 6 AM this 
morning. Mr. al-Iryani declined to say whether the reported 
bombardment meant the government would now consider the 
open-ended cease-fire invalidated. He also declined to comment 
on reports from Aden that gunfire was heard coming from outside 
the city as early as 3 AM. All he said was that when jets fly 
over troops, they will have to fire back. 
  The cease-fire declared by the Yemeni Government in coping 
with last week's UN Security Council resolution on Yemen went 
into effect at midnight last night. In announcing the 
unilateral cease-fire last night, the Yemeni Foreign Minister 
Muhammad Salim Basindwah warned that tacit support for the 
separatists could reignite the fighting. 

</TEXT>

