<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Al-Asnaj Welcomes Sanaa Cease-Fire Decision </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Al-Asnaj Welcomes Sanaa Cease-Fire Decision </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0606213794 London MBC Television in Arabic 2112 GMT 6 Jun 
94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0606213794 </F>
<F P=104>  London MBC Television </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The south Yemeni leaders this evening welcomed 
Sanaa's announcement of a cease-fire. 'Abdallah al-Asnaj, 
foreign minister of the Democratic Republic of Yemen [DRY] 
government that was formed in southern Yemen, said in a 
telephone interview we held with him this evening from Cairo 
that Aden will deal positively with the cease-fire decision. 
  [Begin recording] [Al-Asnaj] The DRY -- government, people, 
and presidency -- repeats its concern for halting the fighting 
in Yemen. It is only natural that we should welcome Sanaa's 
decision on the cease-fire, which will begin at midnight 
tonight. We hope that this decision will not be violated. On 
our part, we have released an official statement saying that the 
DRY welcomes this decision and will comply with the time 
proposed. 
  [Correspondent] Is the cease-fire decision linked to Sanaa's 
statement that it has tightened its control around Aden? 
  [Al-Asnaj] There is nothing to justify saying that control 
of 
Aden was, is, or will be tightened, God willing. Aden and the 
other governorates in the DRY and the nature of Yemen's sons 
will not surrender to invasion or occupation. Aden has 
well-known experience in rejecting and repulsing occupation. 
[end recording] 

</TEXT>

