<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Beilin: Desire for Peace Shared With Syria </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Beilin: Desire for Peace Shared With Syria </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA0706050494 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in English 0400 GMT 7 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0706050494 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Former U.S. Defense Secretary Les Aspin says the 
U.S. Administration understands that an Israeli-Syrian peace 
settlement would require extensive resources, which it is 
willing to commit. He was speaking during a lecture at the 
Davies Institute of Hebrew University in Jerusalem. 
  Deputy Foreign Minister Yosi Beilin, who also spoke at the 
gathering, cited an article from the London-based paper 
AL-HAYAH, which is considered a reliable source on Syria. The 
newspaper's editor wrote that peace talks between Israel and 
Syria are not frozen. He recalled that former U.S. Secretary of 
State Henry Kissinger shuttled between Jerusalem and Damascus 41 
times to help arrange the separation of forces agreement after 
the Yom Kippur War. Israel and Syria have shared outlooks, 
Beilin said: a desire for a peace agreement; recognition of the 
need for withdrawal and U.S. involvement in the process. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

