Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Northern Forces Blast Aden as Cease-Fire Collapses </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Northern Forces Blast Aden as Cease-Fire Collapses </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0706080794 Paris AFP in English 0749 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0706080794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Maher Chmaytelli] </F>
  [Excerpt] Aden, Yemen, June 7 (AFP) -- Artillery duels 
erupted between Yemen's northern and southern forces and shells 
rained down on Aden airport Tuesday [7 June] as fighting 
shattered a ceasefire only six hours after it came into force. 
  The truce, declared unilaterally by President 'Ali 'Abdallah 
Salih's government in the capital Sanaa, had come into effect at 
midnight (2100 GMT) but firing had gone on unabated right up to 
the deadline. 
  Salih forces and those of the southern breakaway state 
declared by 'Ali Salim al-Bid began shelling each other at 6:00 
a.m. (0300 GMT) on a battle front just 20 kilometres (12 miles) 
from this city. 
  The collapse of the ceasefire was followed by an intense 
artillery bombardment of the area around the airport, which the 
northerners have been targeting to destroy it as a base for 
southern planes. 
  But southern fighter-bombers were still taking off on combat 
missions, as a military spokesman accused Salih's troops of 
launching a widespread offensive on all fronts. 
  He said the onslaught had begun at midnight "the very moment 
he (Salih) was announcing to the world he had declared a 
ceasefire." 
  The northerners were "lying" and had dispatched columns of 
tanks to several of the war fronts shortly after the truce was 
announced, he charged. 
  The breakaway southern state was still committed to the 
ceasefire: "all we are doing is defending ourselves and 
repulsing the northern offensive," he said. 
  As the ceasefire collapsed, Sanaa Radio broadcast messages 
to 
the population of Aden saying "the hour of liberation has come." 
  The United Nations Security Council called on June 1 for an 
immediate ceasefire in the civil war which erupted on May 5 
between north and south, four years after they were unified. 
The former South Yemen proclaimed itself independent again on 
May 21. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

