<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Syria, Israel Said To Reach Outlines for Agreement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Syria, Israel Said To Reach Outlines for Agreement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN0706133694 Paris Radio Monte Carlo in Arabic 1200 GMT 7 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN0706133694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris Radio Monte Carlo </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Randah Habib from Amman] </F>
  [Text] Jordanian parliamentary sources have disclosed that 
Syria and Israel have reached an agreement on the broad outlines 
of Israel's withdrawal from the Golan Heights, which Israel 
occupied in 1967, pointing out that the U.S.-brokered 
negotiations between the two sides will resume soon. Citing 
Jordanian Prime Minister 'Abd-al-Salam al-Majali, these source 
said that Damascus has made further steps conditional on an 
Israeli Knesset announcement of the abrogation of the decision 
under which Israel annexed the Golan Heights. The decision was 
issued in January 1981. Syria has also demanded that Israel 
publicly recognize UN Security Council Resolutions 242 and 338 
on the principle of exchanging land for peace, as well as 
Resolution 425 calling for Israel's withdrawal from southern 
Lebanon. 
  The timetable for the Israeli withdrawal remains the subject 
of dispute because the Jewish state is talking about seven years 
while Syria insists that the period should not exceed three 
years, according these same sources. If Israel meets Syria's 
conditions, Damascus will be prepared to raise the level of 
bilateral negotiations -- something that has been demanded by 
Israel. Only then will U.S. Secretary of State Warren 
Christopher resume his shuttle tours between the two states. 
  In another development, Syria is demanding a piece of land 
known as the Palestinian Golan Heights in the Syrian al-Hammah 
area. It was annexed to the Syrian Golan Heights in 1938 and 
then was occupied by Israel along with the rest of the heights 
during the Six-Day War. Israel, however, refuses to withdraw 
from it. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-36239 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes110yy_94002" </HT>


