<H3> <TI>   Jordanian, Israeli Delegates Discuss Borders, Water </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Jordanian, Israeli Delegates Discuss Borders, Water </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Rubinstein: `Good Round' of Talks </H4>

<F P=102> TA0706195394 Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Hebrew 1800 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0706195394 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Hebrew 1800 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=105> Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Elimelekh Ram from Washington] </F>
  [Excerpt] The economic talks between Israel and Jordan 
will be transferred to the Middle East. This was decided at the 
end of another round of talks in Washington. It was also 
decided that a border survey will be performed by joint Israeli 
and Jordanian teams. Elimelekh Ram reports from the U.S. 
capital: 
  [Begin recording] [Ram] The fact that Major General 'Uzi 
Dayan, head of the IDF [Israel Defense Forces] Planing Branch, 
took part in the talks which were mainly economic, attests to 
the security aspect of the decisions made -- whether the issue 
in question is planning a road that would link Israel and Jordan 
or whether it was the establishment of joint projects in areas 
that could be sensitive from a security point of view. Dr. 
Elyaqim Rubinstein, head of the Israeli delegation, sums up the 
current round of talks: 
  [Rubinstein] This was a good round of contacts on both the 
tripartite level of Israel, Jordan, and the United States -- 
which mainly focused on economic issues such as trade, finance, 
and projects -- as well as on the level of the additional talks 
we held with Jordan -- which focused on issues such as security, 
borders, water, and the like. 
  [Ram] The atmosphere at the talks was most optimistic. 
There is a Jordanian readiness to make progress in the 
negotiations. [passage omitted] [end recording] 

</TEXT>

