<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Israel Says Palestinian Radio Be Sited in Jericho </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Israel Says Palestinian Radio Be Sited in Jericho </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0506115994 Paris AFP in English 0854 GMT 5 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0506115994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Jerusalem, June 5 (AFP) -- Israel told the 
Palestinian Authority on Sunday [5 June] they must set up their 
radio station in the autonomous enclave of Jericho and not in 
the occupied West Bank town of Ramallah as planned. 
  The head of the Palestinian Broadcasting Corporation [PBC], 
Radwan Abu-'Ayyash, told AFP he had asked for an official 
meeting after the Israelis notified him of their decision. 
  The PBC had intended to site the studios in Ramallah where a 
pre-1967 transmitter and radio masts are being renovated. 
  "Now we cannot have the studios in Ramallah," Abu-'Ayyash 
said. The town is not part of the autonomous areas. 
  "They have to be in Jericho or Gaza, only the transmission 
will be in Ramallah. 
  "We asked for a meeting to discuss this officially. We 
prefer to have the studios in Ramallah," he stressed. 
  However the Palestinians had managed to get radio equipment 
donated by Germany out of Israeli customs without paying duty 
after a three-week battle, Abu-'Ayyash said. 
  The sound and editing equipment was intended first for 
training new staff, he said. 
  The Palestinians hope to launch a radio service in July 
following the start of autonomy in Jericho and the Gaza Strip 
last month and the PBC has taken on a full-time staff of 17. 
  They also have plans for a television channel, but that will 
take longer to set up, Abu-'Ayyash said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

