<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Envoy Lakhdar Ibrahimi Arrives in Sanaa </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN Envoy Lakhdar Ibrahimi Arrives in Sanaa </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN0806132594 Sanaa Yemeni Republic Radio Network in Arabic 
1200 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN0806132594 </F>
<F P=104>  Sanaa Yemeni Republic Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Brother Lakhdar Ibrahimi, envoy of the UN secretary 
general, arrived in Sanaa this afternoon on a working visit to 
our country, during which he will meet with the brother 
officials in order to be closely acquainted with the current 
developments in the Republic of Yemen. 
  In an arrival statement to the Yemeni News Agency, SABA', 
the 
UN envoy expressed his great appreciation for the responsibility 
entrusted to him in order to carry out this historic mission. 
He added: I take pride in the UN secretary general's 
assignment of this mission to me and by the unanimous support 
this nomination was met with in the Security Council, in 
addition to the Yemeni brothers' welcome of my appointment to 
his mission. Ibrahimi added: I am looking forward to the help 
and assistance of my brothers in this country to perform this 
mission. He went on to say: Dialogue should be restored among 
the brothers and the Yemeni people's love for their country is 
well known. We are looking forward to their cooperation with 
each other and with us in order to return Yemen to its previous 
known march. 
  Concluding, Ibrahimi said: I will not answer questions at 
this stage until we meet with the brother officials and agree 
with them on the way to work together. 
  He was received at the airport by brother Ahmad Dayfallah 
al-'Uzayb, Foreign Ministry under secretary for political 
affairs; Ambassador 'Abdallah al-Uhadi, chief of protocol at the 
Foreign Ministry; a representative of the Presidential Council 
protocol; Dr. 'Awni al-'Ani, UN representative in our country; 
Chadli Benhabib, Algerian ambassador in Sanaa; and (?some 
officials). 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

