<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   'Abd-al-Ghani Calls GCC Statement `Interference' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    'Abd-al-Ghani Calls GCC Statement `Interference' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN0806054494 Sanaa Yemeni Republic Radio Network in Arabic 
0430 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN0806054494 </F>
<F P=104>  Sanaa Yemeni Republic Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Brother 'Abd-al-'Aziz 'Abd-al-Ghani, Presidential 
Council chairman, has stressed our country's concern to 
implement the UN Security Council resolution on the situation in 
Yemen. In this regard, he noted that our country has from the 
very beginning announced that it will abide by UN Security 
Council Resolution 924 which was issued on Wednesday [1 June]. 
  In a telephone interview with Voice of America the day 
before 
yesterday, brother 'Abd-al-Ghani said the Republic of Yemen 
regrets the position of certain Arab states toward the situation 
in Yemen. He stressed that the statement issued at the 
conclusion of the meetings of the Gulf Cooperation Council 
foreign ministers is considered an interference in Yemeni 
internal affairs. 'Abd-al-Ghani praised the position adopted by 
the fraternal State of Qatar rejecting this statement that 
failed to mention the Yemeni unity, which was underlined by the 
UN Security Council resolution. 
  In his interview with Voice of America, 'Abd-al-'Aziz 
'Abd-al-Ghani strongly denied that the Yemeni Air Force planes 
have raided Aden refinery. He said such refineries are the 
property of the Yemeni people and the government cannot destroy 
its own installations. He also stressed that the forces of 
constitutional legitimacy are concerned not to attack any 
position close to any vital installation in the country. He 
stressed that the forces of constitutional legitimacy have 
always taken care not to hit Salah-al-Din Camp, which is 
adjacent to the refinery, despite the fact that devastating Scud 
missiles -- which left behind innocent victims and material 
damage in the civilian neighborhoods where they fell -- were 
being fired from that camp. He underlined the secessionist 
elements' responsibility in hitting the Aden refinery to create 
among the Yemeni people in Aden some kind of bitterness. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

