<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Al-'Attas on Cease-Fire Failure, War Escalation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Al-'Attas on Cease-Fire Failure, War Escalation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   EA0706193194 Aden Democratic Republic of Yemen Radio Network 
in English 1600 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> EA0706193194 </F>
<F P=104>  Aden Democratic Republic of Yemen Radio Network 
in English 1600 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=105> English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Mr. Haydar Abu-Bakr al-'Attas, the prime minister, 
arrived in Abu-Dhabi today from Cairo after a two-day visit to 
Egypt. Mr. al-'Attas had met in Cairo with the Egyptian 
president, Muhammad Husni Mubarak, and held talks with the 
Egyptian officials on the current situation in Yemen. 
  In a press conference, the prime minister said that while 
democratic Yemen announced its preparedness to receive the 
fact-finding commission and to cooperate with it and facilitate 
its mission in order to achieve peace in Yemen and resort to 
dialogue, the Sanaa regime refused to comply with the Security 
Council [resolution] and the advice of the Arab leaders, among 
them President Muhammad Husni Mubarak of Egypt, Shaykh Zayid Bin 
Sultan Al Nuhayyan of the United Arab Emirates, King Fahd 
Bin-'Abd-al-'Aziz, king of Saudi Arabia, and the Syrian 
president, Hafiz al-Asad. He added that the Sanaa regime had 
(?accepted) conditional agreement on cease-fire and then broke 
it up on weak excuses. This proves that there is open 
contradiction in the decision making circle there. 
  He affirmed that the situation in the last 48 hours had 
witnessed a dangerous escalation. The Sanaa regime used in its 
attacks all destructive weapons, including rockets and 
long-range heavy artillery. He indicated that the residential 
quarters and utilities had been the targets of the rockets and 
warplane missiles. Al-'Attas described the shelling of Aden 
refinery as a sign of the times. He said that this operation 
had shocked the Arab and world public opinion. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

