<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Al-'Attas Says South To Demand War Reparations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Al-'Attas Says South To Demand War Reparations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN0806095894 Manama WAKH in Arabic 0905 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> JN0806095894 </F>
<F P=104>  Manama WAKH </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Al-Dammam, 8 Jun (WAKH) -- [Former Yemeni Prime 
Minister] Engineer Haydar Abu-Bakr al-'Attas has announced that 
his country will ask the Sanaa government to pay war 
reparations. He said that the northern Yemeni troops have 
damaged the infrastructure in south Yemen and made thousands of 
Yemenis homeless. 
  In a statement to the Saudi newspaper AL-YAWM published 
today, al-'Attas expressed total amazement over the announced 
number of losses among the northern troops, which was put at 
613. Al-'Attas wondered whether this figure can be reasonable 
[words indistinct], given the use of various kinds of mass 
destruction weapons. 
  Al-'Attas welcomed the final statement issued by the 
Ministerial Council of the Gulf Cooperation Council, saying that 
this statement reflects the GCC members' eagerness to safeguard 
the security and safety of the Yemeni people in particular, and 
those of the region in general. 
  Al-'Attas affirmed that Sanaa has no control over the 
cease-fire decision [la tamluk qarar waqf itlaq al-nar]. That 
is why it has procrastinated over the implementation of the UN 
Security Council resolution, which demanded an immediate 
cease-fire, and failed to honor it since it was announced the 
evening before last. 
  Al-'Attas noted that the international recognition of the 
Democratic Republic of Yemen [DRY] will make Sanaa observe a 
cease-fire. 
  He added that some 60,000 persons have been killed, while 
the 
number of people made homeless has exceeded 100,000. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

